-- Regression: REG-02 crash-canary for tuple destructure (2-tuple).
--
-- # KNOWN GAP: 3+ tuple destructure lands in a future phase (tuple-N
--              codegen). Iron v0.1.4-alpha supports 2-tuples only --
--              Phase 59 P01d shipped 2-tuple destructure via
--              Iron_ArrayLit + is_tuple sentinel; 3+ tuple codegen is
--              a pre-existing gap, not a Phase 67 bug. This canary
--              exercises the supported subset.
--
-- **Motivating Incident.** Phase 37-02's collect_mono_enums_node
-- walker crashed on if/elif/else lowering because of a locally-
-- shadowed struct typedef. The same walker-incompleteness class can
-- re-emerge for any other lower_stmt / lower_expr case, and tuple
-- destructure is particularly risky because the RHS is an expression
-- and the LHS is a binder list -- walker cases that handle one but
-- not the other produce silent data corruption. Phase 66 added
-- _Static_assert on Iron_ArrayLit layout and -Werror=switch-enum;
-- this canary is the runtime regression net.
--
-- **Layout Diagram.** 2-tuple destructure in current Iron lowers to
--   Iron_ArrayLit { is_tuple=true, items=[a_ref, b_ref] }
--   Iron_Assign   { target=a, value=arr[0] }
--   Iron_Assign   { target=b, value=arr[1] }
-- Walker cases that fail to recurse into the binder list drop one or
-- both destructure bindings, producing undefined local variable
-- values at runtime.
--
-- **Fix Summary.** Phase 67-08 added this fixture as a REG-02 crash
-- canary. Exercises the 2-tuple subset supported by current Iron
-- codegen. The 3+ tuple gap is tracked separately and lands in a
-- future phase. CI integration: runs in both Debug and Release via
-- Phase 66-04's build-and-test-release job.
--
-- **Severity.** H (regression potential) -- tuple destructure is
-- used by every Iron program that has a multi-return function, so a
-- walker regression would surface quickly in real code.

func make_pair() -> (Int, Int) {
  return (21, 34)
}

func main() {
  val (a, b) = make_pair()
  println("sum: {a + b}")
}
